      "large_table_impact": false,
      "details": "Stateless enrichment service with no database."
    },
    "verdict": "NOT READY"
  },

  "escalations": [
    {
      "type": "integration_risk",
      "issue": "Inbound timeout (500ms) is structurally incompatible with downstream latency profile (sequential p99 sum: 1150ms; slowest single call p99: 800ms)",
      "reason": "This is not a tuning issue — it is a fundamental design mismatch. The service cannot fulfill its contract with the upstream caller under normal p99 conditions. Shipping this will result in immediate production incidents. Resolution requires architectural decision: parallelize calls, negotiate higher inbound timeout, implement partial enrichment with deadline budgeting, or some combination. This decision affects the upstream caller's contract and potentially the InventoryService team's SLA.",
      "routed_to": "MJ"
    },
    {
      "type": "integration_risk",
      "issue": "No graceful degradation or circuit breakers for downstream failures",
      "reason": "Without circuit breakers, a single slow downstream will cascade into full enrichment failure and potential connection pool exhaustion. The blast radius extends beyond this service — orphaned work generates unnecessary load on downstream services, and connection exhaustion could affect other services sharing the same runtime. MJ needs to define the degradation strategy: which enrichment fields are optional vs required, and what the partial enrichment contract looks like for upstream consumers.",
      "routed_to": "MJ"
    }
  ],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 55,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Timeout mismatch is mathematically provable — sequential p99 sum (1150ms) and even max single-call p99 (800ms) exceed inbound timeout (500ms)",
      "Absence of circuit breakers and graceful degradation is a clear gap",
      "Rollback strategy is adequate for a stateless service"
    ],
